──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
5A. INHERITED SEAL OF PROVENANCE (ISP)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

5A.1 Purpose
The Licensor maintains the Inherited Seal of Provenance: an append-only provenance chain recording descent,
forks, and Adaptations of the Work. Its function is provenance: a public memory of what begat what.

5A.2 When required
If You Share the Work or an Adaptation, You must publish a corresponding Provenance Seal at the time
of public release or as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter.

5A.3 Provenance Seal format (machine-readable)
Each Provenance Seal MUST be published as an LTHING document and MUST include:
(a) seal_id: a unique identifier (SHAKE512 of the canonical LTHING bytes, using the Epoch Rule30 Salt Stream);
(b) attribution_name: "l'Evermoor";
(c) license: "ESL-ANCSA-MRA-IndiModSHA v1.3";
(d) date_epoch_masked: the epoch millisecond value masked by the Epoch Rule30 Salt Stream (Section 1.12), using
    the current Unix epoch milliseconds as input at seal creation time;
(e) artifact: an object containing:
    - name: release name or tag
    - uri: a URL/URI where the released artifact can be retrieved (URI only)
    - content_hash: a cryptographic digest of the artifact encoded with SHAKE512 (custom Keccak-f[1600], c=1024),
      using salt material derived from the Epoch Rule30 Salt Stream
    - hash_alg: the algorithm name; MUST be "shake512"
(f) relation: one of ["original","share","adaptation","aggregation","independent_module_reference"];
(g) ancestors: an array of zero or more parent identifiers and/or parent content hashes sufficient to trace
    ancestry (for Adaptations: MUST include at least one ancestor);
(h) adapter: an object describing the adapter (You), minimally including a stable name or entity string;
(i) signature: a detached ML-DSA-65 signature over the canonical LTHING payload excluding "signature" itself; and
(j) sig_alg identifying the scheme; MUST be "ML-DSA-65" (FIPS 204, NIST Level 3).

5A.3.1 Mandatory hash/salt derivation procedure
For every Provenance Seal required by this Section:
(i) the content hash and seal_id MUST use SHAKE512 (custom Keccak-f[1600], c=1024, r=576);
(ii) the salt MUST be derived from the Epoch Rule30 Salt Stream using the current epoch milliseconds as the sole seed;
(iii) the Rule 30 output MUST also be used as a stream cipher keystream applied to the epoch millisecond value, and the
      masked result MUST be recorded as "date_epoch_masked";
(iv) implementations SHOULD publish a short derivation descriptor (algorithm version, Rule 30
     round count, byte extraction rule) sufficient for reproducibility without disclosing secret signing keys.

5A.4 Canonicalization
The LTHING used for hashing and signing MUST be deterministically serialized: keys sorted, UTF-8, no
insignificant whitespace, CRLF line endings, exactly 4 spaces per indentation level, double-quoted strings,
and stable number formatting.

5A.5 Publication requirements
You must make each Provenance Seal publicly retrievable at a stable URL/URI, and include its URL/URI in the
Attribution LTHING (Section 3.2) under the key:
hash-prov-inh: "<URL/URI to the Provenance Seal>"  (URI only)

5A.6 External anchoring (optional)
You MAY additionally anchor the Provenance Seal by publishing its "seal_id" (or "content_hash") into an
external timestamping or blockchain system. If You do, You must include:
anchor: { system: "<name>", tx_or_proof: "<identifier>", anchored_hash: "<value>" }
Anchoring is permitted but not required; absence of anchoring does not waive obligations under this Section.

5A.7 No falsification
You may not knowingly publish Provenance Seals that materially misrepresent ancestry, authorship, or content
hashes. Honest mistakes cured promptly do not constitute a breach.

